        <body>
            <head><name type="stone">CIIC 47. <placeName type="townland"
                >Castletimon</placeName></name>, Co. <placeName type="county"
                >Wicklow</placeName></head>
            <ab><rs>National Monuments Service Record Number: <ref
                target="http://webgis.archaeology.ie/HistoricEnvironment/?SMRS=WI036-010----"
                >WI036-010----</ref>
                </rs></ab>
            <div type="description" n="site type">
                <head>Site Type</head>
                <p>Unassociated</p>
            </div>
            <div type="description">
                <head>Description</head>
                <div type="description" n="site">
                    <head>Site</head>
                    <p>Lying in a niche at the side of the road overlooking the Potter's River valley and approximately 100 meters north-east of an early ecclesiastical site (Castletimon church and graveyard, WI036-009001-)
                        <ref type="bibliog" target="GRO1997">(<bibl><author>Grogan and
                                    Kilfeather</author>
                                <date>1997</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                            >no. 1006</biblScope></bibl>)</ref>.</p>
                </div>
                <div type="description" n="monument">
                    <head>Monument</head>
                    <p>National Monument in state guardianship No. 304. Granite slab<rs type="material"/>, 
                        <rs type="dimensions"> 
                            <measure unit="metre" type="length" rend="height">1.50</measure>m x
                            <measure unit="metre" type="length" rend="width">0.48</measure>m x
                            <measure unit="metre" type="length" rend="depth">0.25</measure>m
                            (converted from <ref type="bibliog" target="#MAC1945"
                                ><bibl><author>Macalister</author>
                                    <date when="1945">1945</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                        >51</biblScope></bibl></ref>)</rs>. There is a depression at the flat end of the stone which has the appearance of the mortise half of a mortise and tenon joint.
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div type="description" n="text">
                    <head>Text</head>
                    <p>The inscription is <rs type="execution">cut</rs> (up-top) on the rounded angle and is <q>quite clear, though worn, owing to the stone being used as a seat by weary wayfarers</q> 
                        (<ref type="bibliog" target="#MAC1945"
                            ><bibl><author>Macalister</author>
                                <date when="1945">1945</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                    >51</biblScope></bibl></ref>).</p>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="edition" xml:lang="ga">
                <head xml:lang="en">Transliteration</head>
                <ab>
                    <persName><w lemma="NETA-CARI">NETA-CARI</w></persName>
                    <persName><w lemma="NETA-CAGI">NETA-CAGI</w></persName>
                </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="ga">
                <head>Translation</head>
                <p><q>of Nadcaeir of Nadc...</q></p>
            </div>
            <div type="figure">
                <head>Images</head>
                <div type="figure" n="three-dimensional-images">
                    <head>3D Images</head>
                </div>
                <div type="figure" n="photographs">
                    <head>Photographs</head>
                </div>
                <div type="figure" n="drawings">
                    <head>Drawings</head>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <head>Commentary</head>
                <list type="witDeatil">
                    <item n="1"><p>NET(T)A 'champion' (later falling together with NIOT(T)A 'sister's son' when both became <foreign xml:lang="ga"><hi rend="italic">Nad</hi></foreign>-) is frequently found as an element 
                        in personal/kin group names (eg. NETA-SEGAMONAS on <ref
                            target="search.php?ciic=263"
                            >CIIC 263</ref>. Ardmore I and <ref
                                target="search.php?ciic=300"
                                >CIIC 300</ref>. Island). In this case, the NETA spelling would suggest the word meaning 'champion', rather than NIOT(T)A, which can be used alone as a formula word meaning 'sister's son' (cf. <ref
                                    target="search.php?ciic=252"
                                    >CIIC 252</ref>. Gurrane, Co. Kerry).</p></item>
                </list>
            </div>
            <div type="history" n="locations">
                <head>Locations</head>
                <div type="history" n="locations">
                    <head>Found</head>
                    <p>
                        <rs type="found">Lying by the roadside near Brittas Bay in the townland of <placeName type="townland">Castletimon</placeName>, barony
                            of <placeName type="barony">Arklow</placeName>. (GPS coordinates
                            <geo>-6.071241, 52.904532</geo>)</rs>
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div type="history" n="locations">
                    <head>Original</head>
                    <p>
                        <rs type="origLocation">Find location probably original site</rs>
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div type="history" n="locations">
                    <head>Last recorded</head>
                    <p>
                        <rs type="lastLocation">Still at the find site. The location of this stone may be
                            accessed via the <ref
                                target="http://webgis.archaeology.ie/HistoricEnvironment/?SMRS=WI036-010----"
                                >National Monuments Service Historic Environment viewer on
                                www.archaeology.ie</ref>. </rs>
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="history" n="record">
                <head> History of Recording</head>
                <p>Inscription identified by J.C. Toumey in
                        <date when="1854">1854</date>. Known locally as 'the Giant's Stone'.</p>
            </div>
